    "summary": "Phoenician expansion and the founding of Carthage (c. 814 BC, traditional date) represents the westward spread of Levantine Canaanite culture across the Mediterranean, establishing trading colonies from Cyprus to Spain. The Phoenicians of Tyre, Sidon, and Byblos were the preeminent maritime traders of the early first millennium BC, spreading their alphabet (which became the ancestor of Greek, Latin, and ultimately most modern alphabets), their purple dye industry, and their trade networks across the Mediterranean world.\n\nCarthage (Qart-Hadasht, 'New City') was the most important of these colonies — founded according to tradition by Princess Dido fleeing Tyre. Located on the Tunisian coast, Carthage's natural harbor and strategic position made it the dominant western Mediterranean power by the 6th–5th centuries BC, controlling trade routes, extracting tribute from allied cities, and developing its own empire stretching from North Africa through Spain to Sardinia and Sicily. Carthage's Semitic culture, mercantile economy, and oligarchic constitution contrasted sharply with Greek and later Roman models — it employed mercenary armies financed by trade revenues rather than citizen soldiers, and worshipped Ba'al and Tanit. The city's wealth and power made it Rome's principal rival, leading to the Punic Wars that ultimately destroyed it in 146 BC.",
